\section{Introduction}\index{FDTD}
{\LARGE U}nderstanding and predicting electromagnetic behavior is more and more needed in key electrical engineering technologies such as cellular phones, mobile computing, antenna design and EM field measurement etc. \cite{Ryan_Application_FPGA_FDTD}. After the introduction of FDTD by K. Yee in 1966, and with the development in computers the accuracy and flexibility of FDTD for solving electromagnetic problems became soon apparent \cite{Kunz_book_93}. The FDTD technique provides a direct time-domain solution of Maxwell\rq s equations in differential form by discretizing both the physical region and time interval using uniform or non-uniform grid. The explicit nature of the time-stepping algorithm \cite{Anders_Bondeson_book_05} to solve Maxwell\rq s equations conveniently enables the visualization of the electromagnetic fields inside the medium under investigation. This feature is a great benefit compared to frequency-domain methods, like the Method of Moments (MoM) or the Finite-Element Method (FEM). Because this method can solve Maxwell\rq s equations on any scale with almost all kinds of environments, it has become a powerful method for solving a wide variety of electromagnetic problems \cite{Kosmas_FDTD_Model_GPR_Detection}. %In this chapter basic formulation of FDTD technique using Yee algorithm has been introduced. Then FDTD technique has been used to analysis an antenna in transmitting mode. How to use FDTD technique for analysis an antenna in receiving mode for EM field sensor has been discussed. In transmitting mode analysis, H-plane radiation pattern of pyramidal horn antenna has been computed and compared with the measurement and numerical results.
In this chapter, our discussion on the FDTD technique will cover Yee\rq s finite difference algorithm, accuracy and stability, absorbing boundary conditions, initial fields, tine-domain to frequency domain transformation, near-field to far-field transformation and the method how to perfectly plane wave is generated within FDTD lattice. H-plane and E-plane horn antenna radiation patterns are computed using FDTD technique and compared with the published measured results. Diagonal plane horn antenna radiation patterns are also computed. How to used FDTD technique to predict the performance of an antenna in receiving mode as an EM field sensor is also described.


